<refentry lang="en" id="&program;.en">
  <refentryinfo>
    <address>
      &epost;
    </address>
    <author>
      &fnamn;
      &enamn;
    </author>
    <copyright>
      <year>2010</year>
      <holder>&namn;</holder>
    </copyright>
    &datum-en;
  </refentryinfo>
  <refmeta>
    &handbok;
		<manvolnum>1</manvolnum>
		<refmiscinfo class="source">&paket;</refmiscinfo>
		<refmiscinfo class="version">&version;</refmiscinfo>
  </refmeta>
  <refnamediv>
		<refname>&program;</refname>
		<refpurpose>TLS-tunneling tool.</refpurpose>
  </refnamediv>
  <refsynopsisdiv>
    <cmdsynopsis>
      <command>&program;</command>
			<group choice="req">
				<arg choice="plain"><option>service</option></arg>
			</group>
			<group choice="req">
				<arg choice="plain"><option>options</option></arg>
			</group>
    </cmdsynopsis>
  </refsynopsisdiv>
  <refsect1>
    <title>Description</title>
    <para>
			<command>&program;</command> is a compound tool to quickly
			TLS-encrypted or plain TCP-tunnels, locally or to a distant
			host system. All methods available in 
			<systemitem class="library">libgnutls</systemitem>
			are usable for encryption and compression.
			The security functionality is provided by x509v3 certificates.
		</para>
  </refsect1>
  <refsect1>
    <title>Services</title>
		<para>
			The tool acts as frontend to a few subservices. Their names
			are the valid values for <option>service</option>.
		</para>
    <variablelist>
      <varlistentry>
        <term>
					<option>plain-to-plain</option>
        </term>
        <listitem>
          <para>Plain, transporting TCP-tunnel.</para>
        </listitem>
      </varlistentry>
      <varlistentry>
        <term>
					<option>plain-to-tls</option>
        </term>
        <listitem>
          <para>
						Plain input and encrypted output.
					</para>
        </listitem>
      </varlistentry>
    </variablelist>
		<para>
			Each service is described on its own reference page.
		</para>
  </refsect1>
	<refsect1>
		<title>See also</title>
		<para>
			plain-to-plain(1),
			plain-to-tls(1)
		</para>
	</refsect1>
  <refsect1>
    <title>Author</title>
    <para>
			This text was written by &namn;. Permission is granted to copy,
			to distribute, and to modify this document under the terms of
			the European Union Public License, Version 1.0.
    </para>
  </refsect1>
</refentry>

<refentry id="plain-to-plain.en">
  <refentryinfo>
    <address>
      &epost;
    </address>
    <author>
      &fnamn;
      &enamn;
    </author>
    <copyright>
      <year>2009</year>
      <holder>&namn;</holder>
    </copyright>
    &datum-en;
  </refentryinfo>
  <refmeta>
		<refentrytitle>plain-to-plain</refentrytitle>
		<manvolnum>1</manvolnum>
		<refmiscinfo class="source">&paket;</refmiscinfo>
		<refmiscinfo class="version">&version;</refmiscinfo>
  </refmeta>
  <refnamediv>
		<refname>plain-to-plain</refname>
		<refpurpose>plain TCP-tunnel redirector.</refpurpose>
  </refnamediv>
  <refsynopsisdiv>
    <cmdsynopsis>
      <command>&program; plain-to-plain</command>
      <arg choice="req">
				<arg choice="plain"><option>-l</option></arg>
				<replaceable class="option"> lport</replaceable>
			</arg>
      <arg choice="req">
				<arg choice="plain"><option>-r</option></arg>
				<replaceable class="option"> rport</replaceable>
			</arg>
			<group choice="opt">
				<arg choice="plain"><option>-u</option></arg>
				<replaceable class="option"> uid</replaceable>
			</group>
			<group choice="opt">
				<arg choice="plain"><option>-g</option></arg>
				<replaceable class="option"> gid</replaceable>
			</group>
			<group choice="opt">
				<arg choice="plain"><option>-o</option></arg>
			</group>
    </cmdsynopsis>
    <cmdsynopsis>
      <command>&program; plain-to-plain</command>
			<group choice="opt">
				<arg choice="plain"><option>options</option></arg>
			</group>
			<group choice="req">
				<arg choice="plain"><option>-h</option></arg>
			</group>
		</cmdsynopsis>
  </refsynopsisdiv>
  <refsect1>
    <title>Description</title>
    <para>
      <command>plain-to-plain</command> is a standard
			TCP-redirector, listening at a local port and redirecting
			that traffic to another local port, or to a remote host.
		</para>
  </refsect1>
  <refsect1>
    <title>Options</title>
    <variablelist>
      <varlistentry>
        <term>
					<option>-h</option>
        </term>
        <listitem>
					<para>
						Show usage information and list also all values
						to be used for any options, explicitly set on the
						the command line, or left at default value.
					</para>
        </listitem>
      </varlistentry>
      <varlistentry>
        <term>
					<option>-o</option>
        </term>
        <listitem>
          <para>
						Make the listening socket a one-shot service: terminate
						after the first client connection on the local port.
					</para>
        </listitem>
      </varlistentry>
			<varlistentry>
				<term>
					<option>-u</option> <replaceable class="option">uid</replaceable>
				</term>
				<listitem>
					<para>
						Assign the process owner of the listening process. Here
						<replaceable class="option">uid</replaceable>
						is numerical or an existing user name. The default value is
						<systemitem class="username">nobody</systemitem>.
					</para>
				</listitem>
			</varlistentry>
			<varlistentry>
				<term>
					<option>-g</option> <replaceable class="option">gid</replaceable>
				</term>
				<listitem>
					<para>
						Assign the process group of the listening process. Here
						<replaceable class="option">gid</replaceable>
						is numerical or an existing group name. The default value is
						<systemitem class="groupname">nogroup</systemitem>.
					</para>
				</listitem>
			</varlistentry>
			<varlistentry>
				<term>
					<filename class="devicefile">device</filename>
				</term>
				<listitem>
					<para>
						Use the specified baud rate for serial communication.
					</para>
				</listitem>
			</varlistentry>
			<varlistentry>
				<term>
					<replaceable>baudrate</replaceable>
				</term>
				<listitem>
					<para>
						Use the specified baud rate for serial communication.
					</para>
				</listitem>
			</varlistentry>
    </variablelist>
  </refsect1>
  <refsect1>
    <title>Author</title>
    <para>
			This text was written by &namn;. Permission is granted to copy,
			distribute and/or modify this document under the terms of
			the European Union Public License, Version 1.0.
    </para>
  </refsect1>
</refentry>

<refentry id="plain-to-tls.en">
  <refentryinfo>
    <address>
      &epost;
    </address>
    <author>
      &fnamn;
      &enamn;
    </author>
    <copyright>
      <year>2009</year>
      <holder>&namn;</holder>
    </copyright>
    &datum-en;
  </refentryinfo>
  <refmeta>
		<refentrytitle>plain-to-tls</refentrytitle>
		<manvolnum>1</manvolnum>
		<refmiscinfo class="source">&paket;</refmiscinfo>
		<refmiscinfo class="version">&version;</refmiscinfo>
  </refmeta>
  <refnamediv>
		<refname>plain-to-tls</refname>
		<refpurpose>an encrypting TCP-redirector.</refpurpose>
  </refnamediv>
  <refsynopsisdiv>
    <cmdsynopsis>
      <command>&program; plain-to-tls</command>
      <arg choice="req">
				<arg choice="plain"><option>-l</option></arg>
				<replaceable class="option">lport</replaceable>
			</arg>
      <arg choice="req">
				<arg choice="plain"><option>-r</option></arg>
				<replaceable class="option">rport</replaceable>
			</arg>
			<group choice="opt">
				<arg choice="plain"><option>-u</option></arg>
				<replaceable class="option">uid</replaceable>
			</group>
			<group choice="opt">
				<arg choice="plain"><option>-g</option></arg>
				<replaceable class="option">gid</replaceable>
			</group>
			<group choice="opt">
				<arg choice="plain"><option>-o</option></arg>
			</group>
			<group choice="req">
				<arg choice="plain"><option>-c</option></arg>
				<replaceable class="option">certfile</replaceable>
			</group>
			<group choice="opt">
				<arg choice="plain"><option>-a</option></arg>
				<replaceable class="option">cafile</replaceable>
			</group>
			<group choice="opt">
				<arg choice="plain"><option>-k</option></arg>
				<replaceable class="option">keyfile</replaceable>
			</group>
			<group choice="opt">
				<arg choice="plain"><option>-C</option></arg>
				<replaceable class="option">ciphers</replaceable>
			</group>
    </cmdsynopsis>
    <cmdsynopsis>
      <command>&program; plain-to-tls</command>
			<group choice="opt">
				<arg choice="plain"><option>options</option></arg>
			</group>
			<group choice="req">
				<arg choice="plain"><option>-h</option></arg>
			</group>
		</cmdsynopsis>
  </refsynopsisdiv>
  <refsect1>
    <title>Description</title>
    <para>
      <command>plain-to-tls</command> is a protocol converter and
			TCP-redirector. It listens at a local port for plain TCP-traffic
			and then TLS-encrypts and redirects that content to another port,
			locally or to a remote host.
		</para>
  </refsect1>
  <refsect1>
    <title>Options</title>
    <variablelist>
      <varlistentry>
        <term>
					<option>-h</option>
        </term>
        <listitem>
					<para>
						Show usage information and list also all values
						to be used for any options, explicitly set on the
						the command line, or left at default values.
					</para>
        </listitem>
      </varlistentry>
      <varlistentry>
        <term>
					<option>-o</option>
        </term>
        <listitem>
          <para>
						Make the listening socket a one-shot service: terminate
						after the first client connection on the local port.
					</para>
        </listitem>
      </varlistentry>
			<varlistentry>
				<term>
					<option>-l</option> <replaceable class="option">lport</replaceable>
				</term>
				<listitem>
					<para>
						Choose a listening port on the local system. The value
						<replaceable class="option">lport</replaceable>
						is a string of the form <emphasis>[host,]port</emphasis>,
						where <replaceable>port</replaceable> is a service name
						or a numerical port, and the optional <replaceable>host</replaceable>
						is a resolvable host name, an IPv4 address, or an IPv6 address.
					</para>
				</listitem>
			</varlistentry>
			<varlistentry>
				<term>
					<option>-r</option> <replaceable class="option">rport</replaceable>
				</term>
				<listitem>
					<para>
						Choose a port to contact at the remote system. The value
						<replaceable class="option">rport</replaceable>
						is a string of the form <emphasis>host,port</emphasis>,
						where <replaceable>port</replaceable> is a service name
						or a numerical port, and the <replaceable>host</replaceable>
						is a resolvable host name, an IPv4 address, or an IPv6 address.
					</para>
				</listitem>
			</varlistentry>
			<varlistentry>
				<term>
					<option>-u</option> <replaceable class="option">uid</replaceable>
				</term>
				<listitem>
					<para>
						Assign the process owner of the listening process. Here
						<replaceable class="option">uid</replaceable>
						is numerical or an existing user name. The default value is
						<systemitem class="username">nobody</systemitem>.
					</para>
				</listitem>
			</varlistentry>
			<varlistentry>
				<term>
					<option>-g</option> <replaceable class="option">gid</replaceable>
				</term>
				<listitem>
					<para>
						Assign the process group of the listening process. Here
						<replaceable class="option">gid</replaceable>
						is numerical or an existing group name. The default value is
						<systemitem class="groupname">nogroup</systemitem>.
					</para>
				</listitem>
			</varlistentry>
			<varlistentry>
				<term>
					<option>-c</option> <filename>certfile</filename>
				</term>
				<listitem>
					<para>
						Use the indicated file, containing an x509v3-certificate,
						for authentication and encryption for the redirected traffic.
					</para>
				</listitem>
			</varlistentry>
			<varlistentry>
				<term>
					<option>-k</option> <filename>keyfile</filename>
				</term>
				<listitem>
					<para>
						Use the indicated file, containing an ascii armoured key
						that unlocks the above x509v3-certificate.
						If this option is neglected, then it is assumed that the
						certificate file contains an embedded cryptographic key
						structure.
					</para>
				</listitem>
			</varlistentry>
			<varlistentry>
				<term>
					<option>-a</option> <filename>cafile</filename>
				</term>
				<listitem>
					<para>
						Use the indicated file as containing a trusted certificate chain.
						The file should containing a chain of certificates that unlocks
						the above x509v3-certificate.
					</para>
					<para>
						The use of this file is optional, but in case the remote host
						uses strict client verification, the TLS-authentication may
						fail on the host side, in case a use of the chain is neglected.
					</para>
				</listitem>
			</varlistentry>
			<varlistentry>
				<term>
					<option>-C</option> <replaceable>ciphers</replaceable>
				</term>
				<listitem>
					<para>
						Specify cipher suites, priorities, and similar restrictions,
						for use at authentication and encryption in the TLS-protocol.
					</para>
					<para>
						The parameter <replaceable>ciphers</replaceable> is a string
						with default value <emphasis role="bold">NORMAL</emphasis>.
						The usual documentation for
						<systemitem class="library">libgnutls</systemitem>,
						as well as for the major web servers (if they can use TLS/SSL),
						contain further details on the possible contents of this string
						specifier.
					</para>
				</listitem>
			</varlistentry>
    </variablelist>
  </refsect1>
